{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.04,0.69,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38253"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22727"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1932"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4871"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38253"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a two week history of low back pain. He first recognised the pain while he was carrying his 7-year-old grandson. The pain is constant during the day and is worse upon movement. He has difficulty sleeping due to the pain, which he rates as 6/10 in severity. He denies having any morning stiffness, radiation of the pain, limb weakness, bowel and urinary changes. His history includes polymyalgia rheumatica diagnosed two years ago, which is treated with a long term oral corticosteroid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 125/85mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There are no obvious musculoskeletal deformities and no bruising. There is focal tenderness on the lumbar spine. Lateral flexion of the lumbar spine is limited due to pain. Lower limb examination and digital rectal examination are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further investigations","Inflammatory markers","Spinal X-ray","HLA B27 testing","Rheumatoid factor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBack pain is a very common presentation in a primary care setting. Most patients with back pain will not require any additional investigations. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Efurther investigation\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended in this case due to his current corticosteroid treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate investigation in this case is a \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal X-ray.\u003C/strong\u003E Imaging is indicated as oral corticosteroid increases the likelihood of fracture and infections. His acute presentation and night pain are also concerning features, making spinal imaging more appropriate. Other red flags which indicate the need for further investigation include history of trauma, limb weakness, and history of intravenous drug use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA B27 testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in this case as it is non-diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory markers\u003C/strong\u003E (for example, erythrocyte sedimentation rate and C reactive protein) are important to monitor in certain autoimmune conditions including rheumatoid arthritis and systemic lupus erythematous. However, these diagnoses are less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor \u003C/strong\u003Eis a useful investigation if rheumatic disease is suspected. However, a patient whose back pain is autoimmune mediated usually presents with morning stiffness rather than constant localising pain. Therefore in this case, spinal imaging should be prioritised over other investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long term oral corticosteroid use increases the risk of fractures and infections"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd., Polymyalgia rheumatica and Giant Cell Arthritis, Therapeutic Guidelines, 2017. [Available at:https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=polymyalgia-rheumatica-and-giant-cell-arteritis\u0026guidelineName=Rheumatology#toc_d1e47]","NSW Health. Red Flags - Low Back Pain. Pain Management Network. 2014 [Cited 29 Dec 2021] Available from: https://www.aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/212889/Red_Flags.pdf","Ngian G. Rheumatoid Arthritis. Australian Family Physician. 2010 Sep.   [Cited 29 Dec 2021] Vol. 39, No. 9. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/776fb176-083b-4f65-a5c3-f0cc76a416bb/Rheumatoid-arthritis.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-19T10:34:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T12:45:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4057"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","